# Documentation Generation Rule (Core Banking Software)

You are generating modular, AI-consumable documentation for a Core Banking Software project. This documentation will later be read by AI coding agents (including yourself, in a future session) to generate production code — so it must be precise, structured, and unambiguous.

## Non-Negotiable Principles

- **Modular, never monolithic.** One document = one responsibility. Never write a single "complete system" doc.
- **No vague language** in business rules or requirements: never use "usually", "often", "sometimes", "generally".
- **Markdown only**, unless explicitly asked for PDF/DOCX/HTML.
- **No invention.** Never invent business rules, APIs, entities, or glossary terms. If something is missing, insert a `TODO:` marker and ask the user, rather than guessing.
- **No code in this step.** Do not generate implementation code while producing documentation — requirements/use-cases must exist first.
- **Entity lookup fields.** Branch, GL Head, and Account Holder lookups use a single `Autocomplete` field per entity — see [documentation/05-ui-ux/shared/entity-autocomplete-pattern.md](../../documentation/05-ui-ux/shared/entity-autocomplete-pattern.md). Never document legacy ID + select (or search + select) pairs.

## Workflow — Follow In Order

1. Read `AI_INDEX.md` at the repo root. If missing, create it as a linked index of all modules.
2. Read `00-project-overview/{vision.md, business-goals.md, glossary.md, system-boundaries.md}`. Create stubs for any that are missing on a new project.
3. Read `01-architecture/{architecture-overview.md, domain-driven-design.md, security-architecture.md, technology-stack.md}`.
4. Identify the affected business domain (Customer Management, Accounts, Transactions, Loans, Payments, FD, etc.) from the user's request. Only open files relevant to that domain — don't load unrelated modules into context.
5. Generate/update the required files for that module (see structure below).
6. Validate every cross-link resolves to an existing or just-created file.
7. Append an entry to the module's `changelog.md`.

## Required Module Structure

```text
module-name/
  overview.md
  business-rules.md
  use-cases.md
  workflows.md
  api-contracts/
    <one file per endpoint>.md
  database/
    <one file per entity>.md
  sequence-diagrams.md
  acceptance-tests.md
  changelog.md
```

## Size Limits

- Preferred: 200–500 lines per file
- Hard max: 700 lines — split into `-part2.md` and cross-link if exceeded

## ID Conventions

- Business rules: `BR-001`, `BR-002`, ... — sequential, never reused (deprecate, don't delete/renumber)
- Use cases: `UC-001`, ...
- Acceptance tests: `AT-001`, ...

## Use Case Template (`UC-NNN`)

Must include, in order: Actors, Preconditions, Main Flow, Alternative Flow, Exception Flow, Post Conditions, Referenced Business Rules (linked).

## Acceptance Test Template (`AT-NNN`)

Given / When / Then / And — must reference the `UC-NNN`/`BR-NNN` it verifies.

## API Contract File (one per endpoint)

Sections: Endpoint, Method, Request, Response, Validation Rules (→ `BR-NNN`), Error Codes, Dependencies, Acceptance Criteria (→ `AT-NNN`).

## Database Entity File (one per entity)

Sections: Entity, Purpose, Fields, Constraints, Relationships, Indexes, Referenced Rules (`BR-NNN`).

## Architecture Docs

Must cover Services, Security, Deployment, Scalability. No implementation code.

## Cross-Linking

Every file ends with:

```markdown
## Related Documents
- ../relative/path/to/related-doc.md
```

## Before You Finish — Self-Check

- [ ] Folder/file layout matches the Required Module Structure
- [ ] Filenames are kebab-case
- [ ] All `## Related Documents` links resolve to real files
- [ ] IDs are sequential with no duplicates or gaps
- [ ] Every use case has all 7 required sections
- [ ] Every business rule has ≥1 acceptance test
- [ ] `changelog.md` updated

If any box fails, fix it before telling the user the task is done.

## Notes for Cursor

- This rule applies automatically when editing files under `docs/`, `AI_INDEX.md`, `00-project-overview/`, or `01-architecture/` (see `globs` above). You can also invoke it explicitly with `@generate-document` in chat.
- When the user types `/generate-document <module/action>`, treat that as an explicit trigger for this full workflow regardless of which file is currently open.
- Prefer multiple small file edits over one large diff — it keeps each document within the size limit and makes review easier in Cursor's diff view.
